File: eve.info,  Node: Structure,  Next: How eve-mode renders a manifest,  Up: The TJM Manifest

3.1 Structure
=============

A TJM manifest is a JSON file with two top-level arrays:

   • ‘sources’ — a list of media files referenced by the edit.  Each
     entry has an ‘id’ used throughout the manifest and a ‘file’ path.

   • ‘segments’ — the ordered timeline.  Each segment references a
     source, a start and end time (in seconds or ticks), and the spoken
     text.  Optional fields carry per-word timestamps, b-roll metadata,
     speaker identity, tags, and notes.

   A minimal manifest:

     {
       "version": 1,
       "sources": [
         { "id": "clip01", "file": "raw/recording.mp4" }
       ],
       "segments": [
         {
           "id": "clip01-s0001",
           "source": "clip01",
           "start": 12.34,
           "end": 15.60,
           "text": "This is what was said."
         }
       ]
     }

   The TJM v1.1 specification in ‘docs/tjm-spec.md’ defines every field,
including the tick-based timing model, the edit overlay, and the render
contract.


File: eve.info,  Node: How eve-mode renders a manifest,  Next: The raw JSON companion buffer,  Prev: Structure,  Up: The TJM Manifest

3.2 How eve-mode renders a manifest
===================================

Eve-mode presents the manifest as readable text.  Each segment is shown
as a paragraph with its text content.  Markers appear as section
headings.  Deleted words are hidden by default (toggle with ‘C-c C-h’).
Per-word timestamps are hidden unless ‘C-c C-w’ is active.

   The buffer is read-only as prose — you interact through keybindings,
not direct text editing.  The underlying JSON is always kept in sync.


File: eve.info,  Node: The raw JSON companion buffer,  Prev: How eve-mode renders a manifest,  Up: The TJM Manifest

3.3 The raw JSON companion buffer
=================================

Press ‘C-c C-o’ (‘eve-open-raw-json’) to open the underlying JSON in a
companion buffer.  This is useful for low-level inspection or edits that
the structured commands don't cover.  Saving the companion buffer
reloads the eve-mode view.


