13 Architecture
***************

* Menu:

* Two-layer boundary::
* Shared contract::


File: eve.info,  Node: Two-layer boundary,  Next: Shared contract,  Up: Architecture

13.1 Two-layer boundary
=======================

Eve is deliberately split into two independent layers:

   • *The Emacs package* (‘eve.el’) owns the user interface: major mode,
     interactive editing commands, playback integration, asynchronous
     process launching, and parsing of CLI output.  It does not
     implement media-processing logic.

   • *The CLI* (‘cli/’, Python) owns all media processing: manifest
     generation, denoise orchestration, filler policy, timeline
     construction, and FFmpeg invocation.  It does not embed
     Emacs-specific behaviour.

   This boundary means the CLI can be used standalone (e.g.  in CI
pipelines) and the Emacs package can evolve independently.


File: eve.info,  Node: Shared contract,  Prev: Two-layer boundary,  Up: Architecture

13.2 Shared contract
====================

The two layers communicate through:

   • *TJM files on disk* — the ‘.tjm.json’ format defined in
     ‘docs/tjm-spec.md’.
   • *Machine-readable JSON output* — the CLI emits structured JSON when
     called with ‘--json’; the Emacs package parses it.
   • *Stable exit codes* — 0 for success, non-zero for failure.


